    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A cold front forms when a dense, cold air mass wedges underneath a warmer, less dense air mass, forcing the warm air to rise rapidly. This density difference is the primary driver, as the colder air pushes like a slow-moving wall under the warm air, creating a steep pressure gradient. As the warm air rises, it cools and condenses, often leading to the dramatic cloud formation and precipitation associated with cold fronts. The front moves into an area at a speed determined by the temperature contrast and the prevailing wind patterns, effectively sweeping up the warmer air ahead of it.",
